%I A395792 #10 May 11 2026 19:52:04
%S A395792 10,14,20,26,34,70,86,104,106,110,134,154,160,170,194,196,226,230,254,
%T A395792 266,274,310,314,334,350,356,370,386,436,446,464,506,544,566,596,610,
%U A395792 650,656,730,754,826,974,994,1066,1094,1106,1126,1184,1190,1226
%N A395792 Numbers k such that k-3 and k+3 are prime and gcd(k, sigma(k)) is prime.
%C A395792 k is the midpoint of a prime pair (k-3, k+3) differing by 6; this sequence is a subsequence of A087695.
%C A395792 All terms are even since k-3 and k+3 are odd primes. No term is divisible by 3, since otherwise k-3 and k+3 would also be divisible by 3. Hence all terms are congruent to 2 or 4 mod 6.
%C A395792 Most computed terms satisfy gcd(k, sigma(k)) = 2; conjecture: this holds with natural density 1 within the sequence.
%e A395792 For k = 10: 10-3 = 7 and 10+3 = 13 are prime. Also, sigma(10) = 18 and gcd(10, 18) = 2, which is prime, so 10 is a term.
%e A395792 For k = 8: 8-3 = 5 and 8+3 = 11 are prime, but sigma(8) = 15 and gcd(8, 15) = 1, which is not prime, so 8 is not a term.
%t A395792 Select[Range[1230], And @@ PrimeQ[{# - 3, # + 3, GCD[#, DivisorSigma[1, #]]}] &] (* _Amiram Eldar_, May 06 2026 *)
%o A395792 (Python)
%o A395792 from sympy import divisor_sigma, gcd, isprime
%o A395792 def ok(k): return isprime(k-3) and isprime(k+3) and isprime(gcd(k, divisor_sigma(k)))
%o A395792 print([k for k in range(1, 3000) if ok(k)])
%o A395792 (PARI) isok(k) = isprime(k-3) && isprime(k+3) && isprime(gcd(k, sigma(k))); \\ _Michel Marcus_, May 06 2026
%Y A395792 Intersection of A087695 and A392199.
%Y A395792 Cf. A394757, A395258.
%K A395792 nonn,new
%O A395792 1,1
